#2nd re-asked

As of May 2026, the most efficient way to handle distribution for all these platforms simultaneously is to use an orchestrated release tool like [GoReleaser](https://goreleaser.com/). [1]
Instead of managing separate scripts for every platform, you define your tool's metadata once. When you push a new version tag to GitHub, the orchestrator automatically builds your binaries, generates checksums, and pushes updates to npm, brew, AUR (for paru), and more. [1, 2, 3]

## 1. Orchestrated Distribution (GoReleaser)

Modern CLI distribution has moved away from manual scripts toward unified automation. GoReleaser now supports multiple languages including Go, Rust, TypeScript (Bun/Node), and Python. [1, 4]

- How it works: You create a .goreleaser.yml file in your repo.
- What it does: With one command (goreleaser release), it handles:
- npm/bun: Builds your project and publishes the package.
  - Homebrew: Automatically opens a Pull Request to your homebrew-tap with the updated formula.
  - AUR (paru/yay): Generates and pushes the PKGBUILD to the Arch User Repository.
  - WinGet/Scoop: Adds Windows support without extra work. [1, 2, 5]

## 2. High-Speed Installers for 2026

While npm is standard, newer runtimes are significantly more efficient for your users: [6]

- Bun (bun install): By May 2026, Bun has established itself as the fastest option, often performing 10–30x faster than npm for cold installs. If your tool is JS/TS based, recommending bun install -g is the current "pro" efficiency tip.
- ZeroBrew (zb): A Rust-powered drop-in replacement for Homebrew that has gained popularity for being up to 20x faster at re-installations. [6, 7, 8, 9]

## 3. Efficiency via "Single Binary" Shipping

The most efficient distribution method is shipping a statically linked binary. This removes the need for your users to have Node, Bun, or Python installed at all. [10]

- For Bun/Node: Use Bun's native compile feature or Node.js Single Executable Applications (SEA) to turn your tool into a single .exe or binary.
- For Go/Rust: These naturally compile to single binaries, making your curl | bash script incredibly fast since it only has to download one file. [10, 11, 12]

## Summary Table for 2026

| Platform       | Old Way (Manual)           | Efficient Way (2026)                   |
| -------------- | -------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Multi-platform | Manually updating 5+ repos | GoReleaser (Unified Orchestration)     |
| Node/Bun       | npm publish                | Bun (Fastest runtime & install)        |
| macOS          | brew install               | ZeroBrew (zb) (20x faster re-installs) |
| Linux (Arch)   | Manual PKGBUILD            | AUR automation via GoReleaser          |

